#=GF CC   This entry includes endodeoxyribonucleases found in bacteria,
#=GF CC   such as RuvC. RuvC is a small protein of about 20 kD. It
#=GF CC   requires and binds a magnesium ion. The structure of E. coli
#=GF CC   RuvC is a 3-layer alpha-beta sandwich containing a 5-stranded
#=GF CC   beta-sheet sandwiched between 5 alpha-helices [2]. The
#=GF CC   Escherichia coli RuvC gene is involved in DNA repair and in the
#=GF CC   late step of RecE and RecF pathway recombination [1]. RuvC
#=GF CC   protein (EC:3.1.22.4) cleaves cruciform junctions, which are
#=GF CC   formed by the extrusion of inverted repeat sequences from a
#=GF CC   super-coiled plasmid and which are structurally analogous to
#=GF CC   Holliday junctions, by introducing nicks into strands with the
#=GF CC   same polarity. The nicks leave a 5'terminal phosphate and a
#=GF CC   3'terminal hydroxyl group which are ligated by E. coli or
#=GF CC   Bacteriophage T4 DNA ligases. Analysis of the cleavage sites
#=GF CC   suggests that DNA topology rather than a particular sequence
#=GF CC   determines the cleavage site. RuvC protein also cleaves Holliday
#=GF CC   junctions that are formed between gapped circular and linear
#=GF CC   duplex DNA by the function of RecA protein. The active form of
#=GF CC   RuvC protein is a dimer. This is mechanistically suited for an
#=GF CC   endonuclease involved in swapping DNA strands at the crossover
#=GF CC   junctions. It is inferred that RuvC protein is an endonuclease
#=GF CC   that resolves Holliday structures in vivo [1].
